This paper focuses on generating robot motion, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of cost functions and neural networks for style representation suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The potential use of computer vision (cs.CV) for input to the neural network is also possible. Finally, the user study aspect of the paper suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
